Here's the proper approach using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences` for lightweight storage:

**1. In `App.xaml.cs` â€” hook lifecycle events:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        MainPage = new NavigationPage(new NotePage());
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
            WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppBackgroundMessage());

        window.Activated += (s, e) =>
            WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppForegroundMessage());

        return window;
    }
}

// Simple message types
public class AppBackgroundMessage { }
public class AppForegroundMessage { }
```

**2. In your `NotePageViewModel` (or code-behind) â€” save/restore:**

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Messaging;

public partial class NotePageViewModel : ObservableObject,
    IRecipient<AppBackgroundMessage>,
    IRecipient<AppForegroundMessage>
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public NotePageViewModel()
    {
        // Register for lifecycle messages
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.RegisterAll(this);

        // Restore any previously saved draft on launch
        DraftText = Preferences.Default.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    public void Receive(AppBackgroundMessage message)
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        Preferences.Default.Set(DraftKey, DraftText);
    }

    public void Receive(AppForegroundMessage message)
    {
        // Restore draft when app returns (optionalâ€”already loaded)
        DraftText = Preferences.Default.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        // Call this after the user explicitly saves their note
        Preferences.Default.Remove(DraftKey);
        DraftText = string.Empty;
    }
}
```

**3. In your XAML â€” bind the editor:**

```xml
<Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
```

**Key points:**
- **`Window.Deactivated`/`Activated`** are the correct cross-platform lifecycle hooks in MAUI.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text drafts. For large content, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- **`WeakReferenceMessenger`** (from `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`) decouples the lifecycle events from your page/viewmodel.
- Remember to call `ClearDraft()` when the user intentionally saves or discards.
